         <div type="transcription">
            <p><milestone unit="passage" n="16.11b/12b-16.16c"/>
<lb corresp="#a1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>āke</supplied>ne</w><w>ṣäp</w><w>po-yknesa</w><pc>:</pc><w>sa</w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a2"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>jīvi</supplied>te</w><w>na</w><w>tapate</w><pc>:</pc><w>kU<supplied>s</supplied>e</w><w>śau<supplied>lne</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#a3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><gap reason="plain" unit="part"/>e</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>śu</supplied>ddh<supplied>asya</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b2"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><w>ṣek</w><w>yototrä</w><w>yakn<supplied>e</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b3"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>tas</supplied>mād</w><w>vigatarāgebhya<supplied>ḥ</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] entirely, even until it ends (with death) [SKT] he (has recognised the [highest] place and is wise)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (he who) is not tormented during his life [SKT] he who is (not tormented) during his life</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] for the pure (it is always <hi>poṣatha</hi> holiday)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] his manner always succeeds</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] therefore, for those who abstain from their desires</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels"><bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>227-229</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:chakravarti1930"/><citedRange>198-202</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:hahn2007"/><citedRange>60-61</citedRange></bibl></note><note type="remarks">On <ref target="http://idp.bl.uk/database/oo_loader.a4d?pm=IOL%20Toch%20931" type="external">IDP</ref>, recto and verso are reversed.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">Uv.16.11b-c/12b-c <hi>maraṇānte ca sarvaśaḥ / sa vai dṛṣṭapado dhīraḥ</hi> (Uv.16.11c <hi>dhīro</hi>)</note><note corresp="#a1 #a2" type="philcomment">These lines are difficult to locate precisely, because they occur in Uv.16.11-13. Since line a is preceded by lines b-c in the fragment, a1 can only be 11b-c or 12b-c. Accordingly, a2 would be 12a or 13a respectively.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Uv.16.12a/13a <hi>yo jīvite na tapate</hi></note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Uv.16.15b <hi>śuddhasya poṣathaḥ sadā</hi></note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Uv.16.15d <hi>sadā saṃpadyate vratam</hi></note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Uv.16.16c <hi>tasmād vigatarāgebhyo</hi>, here with the regular pausa variant <hi>vigatarāgebhya(ḥ)</hi></note></p>
         </div>
